{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"06317fdc472607c4cfef5c97b53728a1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is showing me the PRM scoring prompt that was previously read. It contains instructions for scoring 5 matched corpus PRs using a 6-dimension rubric. Let me review what's being asked.\n\nThe task is to score these 5 PRs:\n- PR 6265\n- PR 6261\n- PR 6245\n- PR 6243\n- PR 6269\n\nUsing the 6 dimensions (100 points total):\n- NAMING (15%)\n- ERROR_HANDLING (20%)\n- TYPE_SAFETY (20%)\n- ARCHITECTURE (20%)\n- TEST_COVERAGE (15%)\n- DOCUMENTATION (10%)\n\nThe output should be written to `autor_logs/prm_scores.json`.\n\nLet me score each PR based on my knowledge of the diffs described in the prompt. I'll need to use the scoring criteria provided.\n\n**PR 6265: [antig] [Fix] Normalize rewards box in streaming passthrough**\n\nLooking at the changes described:\n- Refactored streaming passthrough to use `_resolve_canonical_level_up_ui_pair()` for normalization\n- Added fallback from `xp`→`xp_gained` and `gold_pieces`→`gold`\n- Added E2E test for streaming passthrough normalization\n- Clean conditional logic\n\nScoring:\n- NAMING (12/15): Good naming with descriptive function names, minor issues with the \"passthrough\" terminology being misleading\n- ERROR_HANDLING (16/20): Good fallback logic, but could have more explicit error handling\n- TYPE_SAFETY (18/20): Good type annotations, minor gaps\n- ARCHITECTURE (16/20): Clean approach, but the passthrough path name is misleading\n- TEST_COVERAGE (12/15): Good E2E test added\n- DOCUMENTATION (9/10): Good comments explaining the why\n\n\n- **PR 6261: [antig] refactor(rewards): migrate to centralized robust numeric extraction**\n\nThe refactor introduces a `DefensiveNumericConverter` class handling messy formats like \"500 XP\", \"1,000\", \"10/20\", and \"unknown\". It integrates with `normalize_rewards_box_for_ui()` through a `_get_raw()` helper and includes comprehensive unit tests covering edge cases. This scores well across most dimensions: naming gets 14/15 for the clear class name, error handling scores 18/20 for the robust fallback chain, and type safety scores 18/20 with proper TypedDict and type annotations.\n\nArchitecture scores 17/20 for clean separation, test coverage hits 14/15 with comprehensive edge case coverage, and documentation gets 9/10 for clear purpose.\n\nFor **PR 6245: fix: stabilize level-up regressions and xp synthesis**, I'm unifying `extract_character_xp()` from game_state while widening `_is_state_flag_true/false` to handle int 1, \"1\", 0, \"0\" from LLM-generated state. I need to fix `xp_from_combat` with proper `is not None` checks and remove the old `_extract_xp_from_player_data` function to clean up duplication.\n\nScoring: NAMING gets 13/15 for the unified helper approach, ERROR_HANDLING scores 16/20 for the explicit checks, TYPE_SAFETY scores 16/20 with some gaps in the old code, ARCHITECTURE scores 15/20 for the cleanup despite some lingering duplication, TEST_COVERAGE scores 11/15 for missing edge cases, and DOCUMENTATION scores 8/10 with good PR comments.\n\nFor **PR 6243: [antig] fix(game-state): widen state flag semantics**, I'm widening `_is_state_flag_true/false` to accept True, 1, \"true\", \"1\" and False, 0, \"false\", \"0\" respectively, using `isinstance(value, int) and not isinstance(value, bool)` to avoid bool/int confusion, with comprehensive tests added.\n\nScoring: NAMING scores 14/15 for clear function names, ERROR_HANDLING scores 17/20 for explicit type checks, TYPE_SAFETY scores 17/20 with good type coverage, ARCHITECTURE scores 16/20 for clean approach, TEST_COVERAGE scores 12/15 for good test scope, DOCUMENTATION scores 8/10 with clear comments. **PR 6269: [antig] Port CR fallback logic to Skeptic Gates** introduces CR fallback logic preferring review state, falling back to status check, then comment pattern with fixes for `set +e -o pipefail`.\n\nFor this PR, I need to fix CR filtering by removing the `and .state == \"success\"` condition from status jq and add a `coderabbitai` alias, then refine the `[approve]` regex by removing the `(?m)^\\s*` and `\\s*$` anchors and add a `CR_SIGNAL` variable to consolidate APPROVED/FAIL logic.\n\nScoring: The bash scripting shows decent structure but inconsistent error handling gets 14/20, while type safety isn't really applicable here so 17/20 for shell patterns. NAME (12/15): shell functions could use more descriptive names, error handling has some gaps but manages acceptable complexity, type annotations fit the context, architecture is clean despite being a single script\n- TEST_COVERAGE (2/15): Not really applicable - it's a workflow script, not tested\n- DOCUMENTATION (7/10): Good inline comments, minor gaps\n\nThe workflow PR scores lower on test coverage since it's a bash script that doesn't require the same test validation as code changes. I should write these scores to the JSON file. Most PRs cluster around 81-83 points, which aligns with the earlier observation that techniques converge to similar scores.\n\nI'm ready to proceed with creating the output file.\n","signature":"765ca05ef23b4afaa1bb565fc407019036d2097473c9f27e5884d1678920e771"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.5","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"61d6b8b7-e16b-4070-b4e5-f34db225e524","uuid":"3e89967d-92d1-45ad-8dc9-93ce76d2b2b9"}
